Contains product information for the Managed Element and its Managed Functions.
This attribute is deprecated.

Deprecated. This is the local date and time for the Managed Element.
The following format is used: YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss

The meaning of each field is as follows:
YYYY = four digit year
MM = two digit month (01=January, etc.)
DD = two digit day of month (01 through 31)
T = time designator (shows start of time component)
hh = two digits of hour (00 through 23, AM/PM not allowed)
mm = two digits of minute (00 through 59)
ss = two digits of second (00 through 59, leap second not allowed)
The hyphen [-] and the colon [:] are used as separators within the date and time of day expressions, respectively.
Deprecated: Deprecated at version 2.3. Functionality replaced by TimeM model.

Parameter Description:
DEPRECATED. This is the timeZone in which the Managed Element resides. 
The possible values for this attribute are defined in the public-domain zoneinfo or Olson database. Locations are identified by a string indicating the continent or ocean and then the name of the location, typically the largest city within the region. See http://www.iana.org/time-zones for more information. Example: Europe/Stockholm.

Parameter Description:
It provides naming context that allows the managed objects to be partitioned into logical domains.
A Distingushed Name (DN) is defined by 3GPP TS 32.300, which splits the DN into a DN Prefix and Local DN, for example DN format: dnPrefix=<DN Prefix>, localDn =<Local DN> Fault Management: dnPrefix does not impact Fault Management, since an NMS recognises a Managed Element by IP address Performance Management (PM): The dnPrefix is present in the PM Data file, Result Output Period (ROP) file, if the dnPrefix attribute is specified, that is, not an empty string. Example: DC=ericsson.se,g3SubNetwork=Sweden
Example: DC=ericsson.se,g3SubNetwork=Sweden

Parameter Description: The value component of the RDN.

ANR criteria for cell relation MO instance to be demoted to lightweight cell relation object.

A neighbor cell relation MO instance is periodically evaluated and demoted when average mobility attempts number per day is less than or equal to this attribute.
Neighbor cell relation MO instance having mobility attempts collected during at least 7 days is considered for demotion based on this attribute.

If empty, threshold based automatic demotion is disabled.
Dependencies: If non-empty, must be less than promoteCellRelMobAttThresh if non-empty.

Parameter Description:
ANR criteria for lightweight neighbor object to be promoted to visible MO instance.

A lightweight neighbor object is internally evaluated before it is created as MO instance if number of average mobility attempts per day is higher than or equal to this attribute.

If empty, automatic promotion and saturation handling are not enabled.
Dependencies: If non-empty, must be greater than demoteCellRelMobAttThresh if non-empty.

List of access categories.

Access category defines which type of access a UE is attempting to perform.

If empty, barring does not occur, regardless if load or rejection conditions are met for sending out barring info.

Under each UacProfile instance, one specific access category is only allowed to be specified in one BarringGroup instance if it affects the same PLMN.

Note: Explicitly defined access categories in one BarringGroup instance, take precedence over empty access categories defined in other BarringGroup instances if it affects the same PLMN.
Change Take Effect: Next unified access control calculation cycle.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can prevent new traffic from being setup.

Parameter Description:
Counter identity.

Identity of counter representing this barring group. Set automatically during MO creation.

Threshold at which maximum probability that a UE is barred occurs.

The amount of UEs that are barred is given by maxBarringProbability.

If cell usage is above this threshold, maxBarringProbability is broadcast in SIB1. Cell usage is defined as number RRC connected UEs to a cell divided by AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe. If AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe is 0, this means that cell usage, based on number RRC connected UEs, is not used in unified access control calculations.
Change Take Effect: Next unified access control calculation cycle.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can prevent new traffic from being setup.
Dependencies: Must be greater than or equal to cellUsageBarringStart.

Parameter Description:
Threshold at which 5 % of UEs are barred.

If cell usage is above this threshold, barring information is broadcast in SIB1. Cell usage is defined as number of RRC-connected UEs in a cell divided by AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe. If AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe is 0, cell usage, based on number RRC connected UEs, is not used in unified access control calculations.

Note: If equal to cellUsageBarringMax, amount of barred UEs is defined by maxBarringProbability.
Change Take Effect: Next unified access control calculation cycle.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can prevent new traffic from being setup.
Dependencies: Must be lower than or equal to cellUsageBarringMax.

Parameter Description:
Maximum barring probability due to high cell usage.

If cell usage is greater than or equal to value specified in cellUsageBarringMax, maximum barring probability is broadcast in SIB1.

Cell usage is defined as number RRC connected UEs to a cell, divided by AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe. If AdmissionLimit::maxConnectedUe is set to zero, this means that cell usage, based on number RRC connected UEs, is not used in unified access control calculations.
Change Take Effect: Next unified access control calculation cycle.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can prevent new traffic from being setup.

Parameter Description:

Parameter Description:

Dependencies: Must be greater than or equal to rejRatioBarringStart.

Parameter Description:

This is the lowest rejection ratio at which barring information is broadcast in SIB1. Rejection ratio is defined as number of rejected UEs divided by total number of access attempts.
Change Take Effect: Next unified access control calculation cycle.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can prevent new traffic from being setup.
Dependencies: Must be less than or equal to rejRatioBarringMax. If equal to rejRatioBarringMax, barring probability broadcast in SIB1 is 100 %.

Parameter Description:
Threshold at which UEs of access identity 1 can be barred.

If barring probability is greater than or equal to threshold, UEs of access identity 1 are barred to the same degree as UEs of access identity 0.

If 100, barring never occurs.

Barring probability is the outcome from calculations made by unified access control. It is defined by settings of following attributes:
- cellUsageBarringStart
- cellUsageBarringMax
- maxBarringProbability
- rejRatioBarringStart
- rejRatioBarringMax

Access identity 1 corresponds to UEs running multimedia priority service traffic.

Following values are recommended:

* 50 is profile5qi is 8 or 9.
* 200 if profile5qi is 5 or 69.

Parameter Description:
Enables energy saving in cell.

Parameter Description:
Duration for cell to periodic transition from IS_ENERGYSAVING back to IS_NOT_ENERGYSAVING state.

Duration is only valid during time period when energy saving is allowed.

When timer is expired:
- If cell energySavingState is IS_ENERGYSAVING, transition to IS_NOT_ENERGYSAVING happens.
- If cell is BARRED with value of NRCellDU::cellBarredReason equal to BOOSTER_CARRIER_SLEEP, transition to NOT_BARRED happens.

If 0, energy saving has no periodic transition.
Change Take Effect: Next time energy saving occasion is triggered.
Dependencies: If 0, esNotAllowedTimePeriod cannot be empty.

Parameter Description:
Name of RAN node.

Allowed characters for value are as follows:
- a-z
- A-Z
- 0-9
- Space
- Apostrophe (')
- Left and right parenthesis ((,))
- Plus and minus sign (+,-)
- Comma (,)
- Full stop (.)
- Forward slash (/)
- Colon (:)
- Equal sign (=)
- Question mark (?)
Character case is preserved. Length of name cannot exceed 150 characters.

For more information, see PrintableString of ITU-T Rec. X.680.

If empty, this value is not sent to AMF.

Parameter Description: The product release of the ManagedFunction.

Whether incoming subscriptions support for Standard Load Reporting is active.

Value -2 means that incoming subscriptions support for Standard Load Reporting (that is, a gNodeB responses on Xn Resource Status Request from another gNodeB and initiates Xn Resource Status Reporting procedure) is inactive.
Value greater than 0 means that incoming subscriptions support for Standard Load Reporting is active.

When active, value also defines default value of maximum number of UEs in RRC_CONNECTED mode for all cells used in Standard Load Reporting.

If NRCellCU::resourceStatusMaxConnUe is not greater than 0, this attribute must be used as maximum number of UEs in RRC_CONNECTED mode for cell in Standard Load Reporting. Otherwise, NRCellCU::resourceStatusMaxConnUe is used.

Not applicable if private extensions are used in 3GPP procedures for Xn resource status reporting.

Whether policy for EPS fallback is considered for rejecting incoming handover with voice service.

If true, handover fails if voice service is not allowed when epsFallbackOperation is set to one of below values:
- FORCED
- FORCED_MEAS_RWR
- FORCED_MEAS_IRAT_HO

For emergency service EPS fallback emergency is considered.

If true, handover fails if emergency service is not allowed when epsFallbackOperationEm set to FORCED.

If false, voice and emergency services are always allowed at incoming handover procedure.

For initial call setup procedure, EPS fallback operation or EPS fallback emergency operation policy is applied, this attribute has no impact.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can cause loss of traffic.

Parameter Description:

If true, PCI conflict is detected. PCI conflict is either collision or confusion. PCI confusion exists if source cell has relations to two neighbor cells where both neighbor cells have same PCI and frequency. Only applicable if PciHandling::pciConflictHandlingEnabled is true.

Parameter Description:
Whether Secondary Node termination for NR-DC is allowed for each ARP.

Bitmap [1-15], each bit corresponds to one ARP value. First or rightmost bit is for ARP1, second bit is for ARP2, and so on.
Each bit has one of following values:
0: Secondary Node termination is not allowed for this ARP.
1: Secondary Node termination is allowed for this ARP.
Bitmap is displayed as decimal value { 0..32767 }.

Examples of decimal value definitions of certain ARP combinations for allowing Secondary Node termination:
* 0: Not allowed for any ARP.
* 1: Allowed for ARP1.
* 2: Allowed for ARP2.
* 3: Allowed for ARP1 and ARP2.
* 4: Allowed for ARP3.
* 5: Allowed for ARP1 and ARP3.
* 15: Allowed for ARP1, ARP2, ARP3 and ARP4.
* 128: Allowed for ARP8.
* 256: Allowed for ARP9.
* 4097: Allowed for ARP1 and ARP13.
* 32767: Allowed for all ARPs.
Dependencies: Must be set to 0 in NrdcSnTerminationUeCfg instances under NrdcSnTermination=SnTerminationProhibited instance.

Parameter Description:
Set of SS/PBCH blocks used for measurements.

Applicable to UE in RRC Idle state or in RRC Inactive state when performing SS-RSRP measurement. Regardless of value of this attribute, SS/PBCH blocks outside of applicable SMTC window are not to be measured.

Defined by bit string with string length equal to or less than maximum number of SS/PBCH blocks within half radio frame.
First leftmost bit corresponds to SS/PBCH block index 0, second bit corresponds to SS/PBCH block index 1, and so on.
Bit value 0 indicates that corresponding SS/PBCH block is not to be measured while bit value 1 indicates that corresponding SS/PBCH block is to be measured.

If non-empty:
- Information element SSB-ToMeasure is broadcasted in SIB2 and SIB4 according to setting.
- At least one bit must be set to 1.

If empty, information element SSB-ToMeasure is omitted in SIB2 and SIB4. According to 3GPP specifications, UE then performs SS-RSRP measurements using all SS/PBCH blocks within SMTC window.
Change Take Effect: When UE read updated SIB2 and SIB4.
Dependencies:
If non-empty, bit string length must be equal to or less than maximum number of SS/PBCH blocks within half radio frame, as defined in 3GPP TS 38.213.
If bit string is provided with length less than maximum length, bit string is padded with 0 up to maximum length before provided into SIB2 and SIB4.

Bit string length must be as defined below:
- If Low-Band and Mid-Band frequencies with arfcnValueNRDl less than or equal to 600000, length must be less than or equal to 4.
- If Low-Band and Mid-Band frequencies with arfcnValueNRDl greater than 600000, length must be less than or equal to 8.
- If High-Band frequencies, length must be less than or equal to 64.

Parameter Description:
Set of slots and symbols, within SMTC measurement duration, configured for SS-RSSI measurement.

Applicable to UE in RRC Idle state or in RRC Inactive state when performing SS-RSSI measurement.

If non-empty, information element SS-RSSI-Measurement is broadcasted in SIB2 and SIB4 according to SsRssiMeasurement.measurementSlots and SsRssiMeasurement.endSymbol settings.

If empty, information element SS-RSSI-Measurement is omitted in SIB2 and SIB4.
According to 3GPP specifications, UE performs SS-RSSI measurement using all slots and symbols within SSB Measurement Timing Configuration (SMTC) measurement duration, in case information element SS-RSSI-Measurement is not provided to UE.
Change Take Effect: When UE read updated SIB2 and SIB4.
Dependencies:
Length of struct member measurementSlots must be equal to or less than number of slots in SMTC measurement duration.
If measurementSlots is provided with length less than number of slots in SMTC measurement duration, measurementSlots is padded with 0 up to number of slots in SMTC measurement duration before provided into SIB2 and SIB4.

Number of slots within SMTC measurement duration = (smtcScs/15 kHz) x (smtcDuration/1 ms).

For all preference UE group identifiers in prefUeGroupList attributes under same parent NRFrequency instance, exactly one NRFrequencyUeCfg instance must exist that combines given preference UE group identifier with an empty ueGroupList.

Parameter Description:
Set of SS/PBCH blocks used for measurements.

Applicable to UE in RRC Connected state when performing SS-RSRP measurement. Regardless of value of this attribute, SS/PBCH blocks outside of applicable SMTC window are not to be measured.

Defined by bit string with string length equal to maximum number of SS/PBCH blocks within half radio frame.
First leftmost bit corresponds to SS/PBCH block index 0, second bit corresponds to SS/PBCH block index 1, and so on.
Bit value 0 indicates that corresponding SS/PBCH block is not to be measured while bit value 1 indicates that corresponding SS/PBCH block is to be measured.

If non-empty:
- UE is configured with information element SSB-ToMeasure according to setting.
- At least one bit must be set to 1.

If empty:
- For intra-frequency measurements on frequency of current PCell or current PSCell, UE is configured with information element SSB-ToMeasure if such information is received from DU over F1 interface.
- For intra-frequency measurements on frequency of current PCell or current PSCell, UE is not configured with information element SSB-ToMeasure if such information is not received from DU over F1 interface.
- If not intra-frequency measurements, UE is not configured with information element SSB-ToMeasure.
According to 3GPP specifications, UE then performs SS-RSRP measurement using all SS/PBCH blocks within SMTC window.
Dependencies:
If non-empty, bit string length must be equal to or less than maximum number of SS/PBCH blocks within half radio frame, as defined in 3GPP TS 38.213.
If bit string is provided with length less than maximum length, bit string is padded with 0 up to maximum length before sent to UE.

Bit string length must be as defined below:
- If Low-Band and Mid-Band frequencies with NRFrequency::arfcnValueNRDl less than or equal to 600000, length must be less than or equal to 4.
- If Low-Band and Mid-Band frequencies with NRFrequency::arfcnValueNRDl greater than 600000, length must be less than or equal to 8.
- If High-Band frequencies, length must be less than or equal to 64.

Parameter Description:
Set of slots and symbols, within SMTC measurement duration, used for SS-RSSI measurement.

Applicable to UE in RRC Connected state when performing SS-RSSI measurement on serving or non-serving frequencies.

If non-empty:
- UE is configured with information element SS-RSSI-Measurement according to SsRssiMeasurement.measurementSlots and SsRssiMeasurement.endSymbol settings.

If empty:
- For intra-frequency measurements on frequency of current PCell or current PSCell, UE is configured with information element SS-RSSI-Measurement if such information is received from DU over F1 interface.
- For intra-frequency measurements on frequency of current PCell or current PSCell, UE is not configured with information element SS-RSSI-Measurement if such information is not received from DU over F1 interface.
- If not intra-frequency measurements, UE is not configured with information element SS-RSSI-Measurement.
According to 3GPP specifications, UE performs SS-RSSI measurement using all slots and symbols within SSB Measurement Timing Configuration (SMTC) measurement duration, in case information element SS-RSSI-Measurement is not provided to UE.
Dependencies:
Length of struct member measurementSlots must be equal to or less than number of slots in SMTC measurement duration.
If measurementSlots is provided with length less than number of slots in SMTC measurement duration, measurementSlots is padded with 0 up to number of slots in SMTC measurement duration before sent to UE.

Number of slots within SMTC measurement duration = (NRFrequency::smtcScs/15 kHz) x (NRFrequency::smtcDuration/1 ms).

Parameter Description: The value component of the RDN.

Preference UE group selection criteria.

Defines selection criteria that UE needs to fulfill to belong to the Preference UE group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to True, UE fulfills Preference UE group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to False or Unknown, UE does not fulfill Preference UE group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to True for more than one Preference UE group instance, UE belongs to the Preference UE group instance with highest setting of prefUeGroupPriority.

Syntax:
======
The syntax of selection criteria is defined using Backus-Naur form.

<SelectionCriteria> ::= <ParentExpressionList> | ""
<ParentExpressionList> ::= <ParentExpressionList> <AndOr> < ParentExpressionList> | <Not>? "(" <ParentExpressionList> ")" | <ExpressionList> | <FlowExpressionList>
<FlowExpressionList> ::= <FlowExpressionList> <AndOr> <FlowExpressionList> | <Not>? <FlowExpression>
<FlowExpression> ::= "["<ExpressionList>"]"
<ExpressionList> ::= <ExpressionList> <AndOr> <ExpressionList> | <Not>? "(" <ExpressionList> ")" | <Not>? <VariableExpression>
<VariableExpression> ::= <Variable> <RelationalOperator> <Value> | <Variable> "==" "{" <ValueList> "}"
<ValueList> ::= <Value> "," <ValueList> | <Value>

<Variable> ::= "5qi" | "arp" | "cgrole" | "chipset" | "imeisv" | "imeisvn" | "imeitac" | "plmn" | "qci" | "redcapue" | "rfsp" | "rrcEstResCause" | "snssai" | "spid"

<AndOr> ::= "&&" | "||"
<Not> ::= "!"

<RelationalOperator> ::= "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">=" | ">"

A list of possible values can be specified in the form <Variable> == {<value1>, <value2>, ... , <valueN>}. This statement is equivalent to writing (<Variable> == <value1> || <Variable> == <value2> || ... || <Variable> == <valueN>).

Up to 4 <FlowExpression> can be defined in <SelectionCriteria>.

Whitespaces are allowed in the string for improved readability and are removed prior to evaluation.

Question mark (?) means zero or one occurrence. For example, <Not>? makes <Not> optional.

Syntax is case sensitive.

Semantic:
========
Selection criteria evaluation is defined by the following semantic rules.

If empty or set to empty string "", selection criteria always evaluates to True.

Selection criteria evaluation is done per UE with the current applicable UE <Variable> values as input. List of UE <Variable> values that are applicable to NR standalone and EN-DC, respectively, is defined in Variable Definitions section below.

Selection criteria for a UE is evaluated separately for each flow using applicable flow-dependent <Variable> together with rest of applicable UE <Variable>. For UE in NR standalone flow-dependent <Variable> 5qi, arp, and snssai are applicable. For UE in EN-DC flow-dependent <Variable> qci, and arp are applicable.

Selection criteria evaluates to True if any of the flows evaluates to True. If UE does not have a flow, flow-dependent <Variable> values are evaluated as unknown variable values. If selection criteria shall match combination of flow-dependent <Variable>, then <FlowExpression> and <FlowExpressionList> must be used.
Note: An <ExpressionList> defined as <VariableExpression> && <VariableExpression>, for which both <VariableExpression> relate to flow-dependent <Variable>, needs special attention.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi==5 && 5qi==9" always evaluate to False for UE in NR standalone even if UE has one flow with 5qi=5 and one flow with 5qi=9.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi>=7 && 5qi<=11" will evaluate to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi between 7 and 11.

<FlowExpression> is defined as "["<ExpressionList>"]" and indicates that an <ExpressionList> is evaluated per QoS flow independent of other <ExpressionList>.

Example: <FlowExpressionList> = "[5qi==1] && [5qi==5]" evaluates to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi=1 and any flow with 5qi=5. In the example, [5qi==1] must match one flow, and [5qi==5] must match one flow.

<VariableExpression> evaluates to Unknown if <Variable> is not known or if the <Variable> value is not valid.
<VariableExpression> evaluates to True or False if <Variable> value is known and valid.

<Value> "ref" is a special <Value> of <Variable> representing <ValueList> defined via corresponding reference attribute. For <Variable> chipset, and imeisv, corresponding reference attribute is chipsetRef, and imeiSvRef respectively.

If reference attribute is empty, represented <ValueList> is empty.

The logical operators <AndOr> and <Not> apply three way logic as defined below:

F=False; T=True; U=Unknown
A=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>
B=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>

NOT operator:
A !A
-----------------
F T
U U
T F

AND operator:
A B A && B
-------------------
F F F
F T F
F U F
T F F
T T T
T U U
U F F
U T U
U U U

OR operator:
A B A || B
------------------
F F F
F T T
F U U
T F T
T T T
T U T
U F U
U T T
U U U

Variable Definitions:
=================

Allowed <Value> and <RelationalOperator> depend on <Variable> with limitations given below.

5qi:
5G QoS Identifier (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

arp:
Priority Level part of the Allocation and Retention Priority (3GPP TS 38.413, 3GPP TS 36.423). Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..15 given in decimal.

cgrole:
Cell group role. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: mcg or scg, where mcg is only applicable to NR standalone.

chipset:
Chipset identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<vendor>.<variant>.<version>" matched by regular expression "(1[0-6]|[0-9])\\.(6[0-4]|[1-5]?[0-9])\\.(12[0-8]|1[01][0-9]|[1-9]?[0-9])", or a string constant "ref".

Description: Chipset identifier composed of three distinct elements:
- vendor: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..16
- variant: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..64
- version: 1-3 digit decimal number in range 0..128

UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting are represented internally as 0.0.0.

Example values: 0.0.0, 1.1.1, 1.2.3, 16.10.100, 16.64.128, ref.

imeisv:
International Mobile Station Equipment Identity Software Version. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<TAC><SNR><SVN>" matched by regular expression "[0-9]{10}[0-9fF]{4}[0-9]{2}", or string constant "ref".

Description: IMEISV composed of three distinct elements:
- TAC (Type Allocation Code): 8 digit decimal number
- SNR (or SN, Serial Number): 2 digit decimal number + 4 digit hexa-decimal number, last four digits are automatically masked with 0xFFFF to match with masked IMEISV
- SVN (Software Version Number): 2 digit decimal number

Example values: 1234567890123456, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890ffff12, ref.

imeitac:
Type Allocation Code (TAC) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 8 digit decimal number.

imeisvn:
Software Version Number (SVN) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 2 digit decimal number.

plmn:
Public Land and Mobile Network identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: A string matched by regular expression "[02-79][0-9][0-9]-[0-9][0-9][0-9]?".

Example values: 070-007, 070-07, 234-56.

qci:
QoSClass Identifier (3GPP TS 23.401). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

redcapue:
Reduced Capabilities UE indicator. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: Boolean
Description: RedCap UE identification received via LCID in MSG3 (see 3GPP TS 38.331).

rfsp:
Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

rrcEstResCause:
RRC establishment cause or RRC resume cause. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: One of emergency, highPriorityAccess, mt-Access, mo-Signaling, mo-Data, mo-VoiceCall, mo-VideoCall, mo-SMS, mps-PriorityAccess, or mcs-PriorityAccess.
Description: Establishment cause value received in RRC Setup Request message or resume cause received
in RRC Resume Request message (see 3GPP TS 38.331).
The received establishment cause or resume cause is valid in UE grouping framework when performing UE group evaluation during time specified by corresponding validity time attribute value in MO class UeGroupSelection.

snssai:
Single Network Slice Selection Assistance Information (3GPP TS 23.003). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: input option 1: String in format "<SST><SD>" matched by regular expression [0][x][0-9a-fA-F]{8} (8 digit hexa-decimal number).
Value: input option 2: Integer in range 0x0..0xffffffff given in hexadecimal.
Description: S-NSSAI is composed of two distinct elements:
- SST (Slice/Service Type): 2 digit hexa-decimal number
- SD (Slice Differentiator): 6 digit hexa-decimal number
The SD field has a reserved value "no SD value associated with the SST" defined as hexadecimal FFFFFF/ffffff.

Example values, input option 1:
- 0x050000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x2effffff (SST=0x2e,SD=0xffffff // no SD associated with the SST)

Example values, input option 2:
- 0x1 (SST=0x00,SD=0x000001)
- 0x50000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x150000EE (SST=0x15,SD=0x0000EE)

spid:
Subscriber Profile ID for RAT/Frequency Priority (3GPP TS 36.300). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

Operator Precedence Order:
=======================
The logical and relation operators are evaluated according to the precedence order listed below.

---------------------------------------------
1 (highest precedence)
< Less than
<= Less than or equal
> Greater than
>= Greater than or equal
== Equal
!= Not equal
-------------------------------------------
2 ! (Not)
---------------------------------------------
3 && (And)
---------------------------------------------
4 (lowest precedence)
|| (Or)
---------------------------------------------

The NOT operator "!" negates the following <ParentExpressionList>, <VariableExpression>, <FlowExpression> or an <ExpressionList> encapsulated in parenthesis.
Therefore, expression !a==b && c==d is equivalent to ((!(a==b)) && (c==d)) and different from !(a==b && c==d).
Expression !a==b and !(a==b) are equivalent.

Since AND operator "&&" has higher precedence than OR operator "||", a<b || a<c && c<d is equivalent to (a<b || (a<c && c<d)). Surround expression list including OR operator with parenthesis to force OR operator to be evaluated before AND operators outside of the expression list, for example (a<b || a<c) && c<d.

Examples:
=========

Simple one valued expressions:
plmn == 234-56
spid == 1
cgrole == mcg
arp > 3
snssai == 0xfedcba98
rrcEstResCause == mo-VoiceCall
imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12

imeisv == ref //Special <value> ref represents <ValueList> defined via imeiSvRef.
chipset == ref
chipset == 1.1.1 //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1.
chipset == 0.0.0 //Matches all UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting.

Value list expressions:
spid == {8,9,10,1,155}
!plmn == {234-56, 434-567}
chipset == {1.1.1, 1.1.2, 1.1.3, ref} //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1, 2 or 3, or the corresponding vendor, variant and version defined via chipsetRef.
imeisv == {1234567890FFFF12, ref, 1234567890FFFF13} //Matches all UEs with imeisv: TAC = 12345678, SNR = 90FFFF and SVN = 12 or 13, or the corresponding TAC, SN and SVN defined via imeiSvRef.

Equivalent expressions using ||:
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) //Equals to spid == {8, 9, 10, 1, 155}.
!(plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567) //Equals to !plmn == {234-56, 434-567}.

imeisv == ref || imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12|| imeisv == 1234567890FFFF13 //Equals to imeisv == {ref, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890FFFF13}.
chipset == 1.1.1 || chipset == ref || chipset == 1.1.2 // Equals to chipset == {1.1.1, ref, 1.1.2}.

Negative expressions:
!5qi==1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
5qi!=1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

Negative <FlowExpressions> that produce same result:
[!5qi==1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
[5qi!=1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

<FlowExpressionList> negative expressions:
!([5qi==1]) //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.
![5qi==1] //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.

Mixed examples:
spid == 1 && cgrole == mcg
!(spid != 1 || cgrole != mcg)
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) && (plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567)

Precedence given by "()" and sequence alter the evaluation order and result:
[5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5] //Equals to ([5qi==1] && chipset==ref) || (imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
([5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
chipset==ref || [5qi==1] && [5qi==5] && imeisv==ref

Examples of selection criteria that shall be avoided since they will always be evaluated to False. <FlowExpression> can be used in these cases.
5qi==5 && 5qi==9
snssai==0x15000000 && snssai==0x17000000
arp==5 && arp==10
qci==5 && qci==9

Example of selection criteria for UE variable snssai:
snssai>=15000000 && snssai<=15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 regardless of value of S-NSSAI SD part.
snssai==15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 and S-NSSAI SD part value equal to FFFFFF, meaning no SD value associated with the SST.

Flow expressions combined with UE variables:
plmn == 234-56 && [5qi==1] && [5qi==9] //Matches UE which has plmn equal to 234-56, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1, and any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9.
chipset==1.5.32 && [5qi==9] && ![5qi==1] //Matches UE which has chipset identifier equal to 1.5.32, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9, and no QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1.
[5qi==1 && snssai == 0xfedcba98] || ([5qi==2] && [snssai == 0xfedcba77]) //Matches UE which has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba98, or has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 2 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba77.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can cause loss of traffic.

Parameter Description: The value component of the RDN.
Label for free use.

Initial uplink configuration for EN-DC and NR-DC.

Whether to use MCG or SCG leg for uplink at initial state. Set when dual connectivity is configured.
The value component of the RDN.

Buffer threshold for uplink PDCP split for capable UE instances.

Specifies buffer level where capable UE instances can split data on both main and secondary leg when primary path is SCG.
A capable UE is a UE with dual connectivity supporting split DRB with uplink on both MCG and SCG. This UE can submit uplink PDCP PDUs to both primary RLC entity and secondary RLC entity if total amount of PDCP and RLC data volume for initial transmission in two associated RLC entities is equal or larger than used threshold.
If 0, uplink PDCP split is always active for capable UE instances.
If -1, used threshold is infinity meaning that PDCP split is not allowed even for capable UE instances.
The attribute is common for EN-DC and NR-DC.
If empty, used threshold will be automatically controlled for EN-DC users and set to infinity for NR-DC users.

Without license for LTE-NR Uplink Aggregation a value of infinity is used for EN-DC and NR-DC users.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can cause loss of traffic.

Parameter Description:
Buffer threshold for uplink PDCP split for capable UE instances when primary path is MCG.

This attribute is only applicable to EN-DC UEs. For NR-DC UEs used threshold is infinity meaning that PDCP split is not allowed when primary path is MCG.
Only applicable if license for LTE-NR Uplink Aggregation is present and feature is active.

Following settings are possible:
- If empty and value for ulDataSplitThreshold is also empty, threshold is 51200.
- If empty and value for ulDataSplitThreshold is non-empty, value according to ulDataSplitThreshold is used.
- If -1, threshold is infinity meaning that PDCP split is not allowed.
- If 0, UL PDCP split is always active.
- Value -1 is recommended when NRCellDU::endcUlLegSwitchEnabled is true and a low value is set for NRCellDU::endcUlNrLowQualThresh.
- Values 0 to 1600 are only recommended for operators for temporary testing purposes.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can cause loss of traffic.

Whether deprecation handling for rsrpPCellCandidateB1 in TrStSaCellProfileUeCfg is enabled.

Whether deprecation handling for rsrpPCellCandidateB1 in TrStSaCellProfileUeCfg and for rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset in TrStSaEUtranFreqRelProfileUeCfg is enabled.

If true, deprecation handling as below apply:
- At create of TrStSaCellProfileUeCfg instance:
Set rsrpPCellCandidateB2.threshold1 to -29
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.hysteresis to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.hysteresis
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.threshold to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.threshold2EUtra
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.timeToTrigger to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.timeToTrigger

- At update of rsrpPCellCandidateB1 corresponding update of replacing rsrpPCellCandidateB2 is done as described below:
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.hysteresis to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.hysteresis
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.threshold to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.threshold2EUtra
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1.timeToTrigger to rsrpPCellCandidateB2.timeToTrigger

- At create of TrStSaEUtranFreqRelProfileUeCfg instance:
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset to rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets.threshold2EUtraOffset
Set rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets.threshold1Offset to 0

- At update of rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset corresponding update of replacing rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets is done as described below:
Copy rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset to rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets.threshold2EUtraOffset

If false, no deprecation handling is applied for rsrpPCellCandidateB1 and rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset.

Node always uses rsrpPCellCandidateB2 configured in TrStSaCellProfileUeCfg instance. Updating rsrpPCellCandidateB2 never updates deprecated rsrpPCellCandidateB1.
Node always uses rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets configured in TrStSaEUtranFreqRelProfileUeCfg instance. Updating rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets never updates deprecated rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset.

Disabling deprecation handling prevents rsrpPCellCandidateB2 in TrStSaEUtranFreqRelPro MO class from being overwritten by deprecation handling for rsrpPCellCandidateB1.
Disabling deprecation handling prevents rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets in TrStSaEUtranFreqRelProfileUeCfg MO class from being overwritten by deprecation handling for rsrpPCellCandidateB1Offset.

Set to false when using management system where rsrpPCellCandidateB2 in TrStSaCellProfileUeCfg MO class and rsrpPCellCandidateB2Offsets in TrStSaEUtranFreqRelProfileUeCfg MO class are visible.

Only applicable if license for Advanced Multi-Layer Coordination is present and feature is active.
Only applicable to Low-Band and Mid-Band cells.

Parameter Description: The value component of the RDN.

Whether uplink cell load is considered when selecting cells.

Only applicable if following conditions are fulfilled:

Only applicable if license for NR Advanced Multi-Layer Coordination is present and feature is active.

Parameter Description:
Whether uplink cell load can be considered when selecting cells.

Value is true only if all following conditions are fulfilled:
- There is an NRCellRelation instance where sCellCandidate is ALLOWED or ONLY_ALLOWED_FOR_DL, and caStatusActive has been true at some point in time since Xn-interface between gNodeBs was established, towards a cell in a gNodeB that indicates Advanced MLC capabilities uplink load awareness support, full support and uplink load awareness set to ON.

Uplink cell load is only considered when selecting cells if:
- Value of this attribute is true.
- Value of ulCellLoadAwareEnabled is true.
- License for NR Advanced Multi-Layer Coordination is present and feature is active.

Aggregated bandwidth threshold.

Used in bandwidth-triggered inter-system handover function to decide if inter-system handover to E-UTRAN shall be triggered.

If aggregated downlink bandwidth (MHz) of current serving NR cell(s) in coverage is lower than or equal to threshold inter-system handover to E-UTRAN might be triggereded. Downlink bandwidth per serving cell corresponds to value of NRSectorCarrier::bSChannelBwDL under GNBDUFunction instance.

Parameter Description:
Criterion for better UE configuration.

Defines a better UE configuration candidate relative to the current UE configuration. Expressed as percentage better estimated throughput based on the configured bandwidth of respective UE configuration.

For NR Advanced Multi-Layer Coordination feature and Uplink-Aware Advanced Multi-Layer Coordination feature, cell load is also used when calculating estimated throughput.

Absolute offset criterion in downlink for better UE configuration.

Defines a better UE configuration candidate than current UE configuration. Expressed as an absolute offset above current estimated downlink cell weight for current UE configuration.

Absolute offset criterion in uplink for better UE configuration.

Defines a better UE configuration candidate than current UE configuration. Expressed as an absolute offset above current estimated uplink cell weight for current UE configuration.

If 0, volume buffer monitoring is disabled.

Parameter Description:
UE admission group selection criteria.

Defines selection criteria that UE needs to fulfill to belong to UE admission group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to True, UE fulfills UE admission group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to False or Unknown, UE does not fulfill UE admission group instance.

If selection criteria evaluates to True for more than one UE admission group instance, UE belongs to UE admission group instance with highest setting of ueAdmissionGroupPriority.

Syntax:
======
The syntax of selection criteria is defined using Backus-Naur form.

<SelectionCriteria> ::= <ParentExpressionList> | ""
<ParentExpressionList> ::= <ParentExpressionList> <AndOr> < ParentExpressionList> | <Not>? "(" <ParentExpressionList> ")" | <ExpressionList> | <FlowExpressionList>
<FlowExpressionList> ::= <FlowExpressionList> <AndOr> <FlowExpressionList> | <Not>? <FlowExpression>
<FlowExpression> ::= "["<ExpressionList>"]"
<ExpressionList> ::= <ExpressionList> <AndOr> <ExpressionList> | <Not>? "(" <ExpressionList> ")" | <Not>? <VariableExpression>
<VariableExpression> ::= <Variable> <RelationalOperator> <Value> | <Variable> "==" "{" <ValueList> "}"
<ValueList> ::= <Value> "," <ValueList> | <Value>

<Variable> ::= "5qi" | "arp" | "cgrole" | "chipset" | "imeisv" | "imeisvn" | "imeitac" | "plmn" | "qci" | "redcapue" | "rfsp" | "rrcEstResCause" | "snssai" | "spid"

<AndOr> ::= "&&" | "||"
<Not> ::= "!"

<RelationalOperator> ::= "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">=" | ">"

A list of possible values can be specified in the form <Variable> == {<value1>, <value2>, ... , <valueN>}. This statement is equivalent to writing (<Variable> == <value1> || <Variable> == <value2> || ... || <Variable> == <valueN>).

Up to 4 <FlowExpression> can be defined in <SelectionCriteria>.

Whitespaces are allowed in the string for improved readability and are removed prior to evaluation.

Question mark (?) means zero or one occurrence. For example, <Not>? makes <Not> optional.

Syntax is case sensitive.

Semantic:
========
Selection criteria evaluation is defined by the following semantic rules.

If empty or set to empty string "", selection criteria always evaluates to True.

Selection criteria evaluation is done per UE with the current applicable UE <Variable> values as input. List of UE <Variable> values that are applicable to NR standalone and EN-DC, respectively, is defined in Variable Definitions section below.

Selection criteria for a UE is evaluated separately for each flow using applicable flow-dependent <Variable> together with rest of applicable UE <Variable>. For UE in NR standalone flow-dependent <Variable> 5qi, arp, and snssai are applicable. For UE in EN-DC flow-dependent <Variable> qci, and arp are applicable.

Selection criteria evaluates to True if any of the flows evaluates to True. If UE does not have a flow, flow-dependent <Variable> values are evaluated as unknown variable values. If selection criteria shall match combination of flow-dependent <Variable>, then <FlowExpression> and <FlowExpressionList> must be used.
Note: An <ExpressionList> defined as <VariableExpression> && <VariableExpression>, for which both <VariableExpression> relate to flow-dependent <Variable>, needs special attention.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi==5 && 5qi==9" always evaluate to False for UE in NR standalone even if UE has one flow with 5qi=5 and one flow with 5qi=9.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi>=7 && 5qi<=11" will evaluate to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi between 7 and 11.

<FlowExpression> is defined as "["<ExpressionList>"]" and indicates that an <ExpressionList> is evaluated per QoS flow independent of other <ExpressionList>.

Example: <FlowExpressionList> = "[5qi==1] && [5qi==5]" evaluates to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi=1 and any flow with 5qi=5. In the example, [5qi==1] must match one flow, and [5qi==5] must match one flow.

<VariableExpression> evaluates to Unknown if <Variable> is not known or if the <Variable> value is not valid.
<VariableExpression> evaluates to True or False if <Variable> value is known and valid.

<Value> "ref" is a special <Value> of <Variable> representing <ValueList> defined via corresponding reference attribute. For <Variable> chipset, and imeisv, corresponding reference attribute is chipsetRef, and imeiSvRef respectively.

If reference attribute is empty, represented <ValueList> is empty.

The logical operators <AndOr> and <Not> apply three way logic as defined below:

F=False; T=True; U=Unknown
A=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>
B=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>

NOT operator:
A !A
-----------------
F T
U U
T F

AND operator:
A B A && B
-------------------
F F F
F T F
F U F
T F F
T T T
T U U
U F F
U T U
U U U

OR operator:
A B A || B
------------------
F F F
F T T
F U U
T F T
T T T
T U T
U F U
U T T
U U U

Variable Definitions:
=================

Allowed <Value> and <RelationalOperator> depend on <Variable> with limitations given below.

5qi:
5G QoS Identifier (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

arp:
Priority Level part of the Allocation and Retention Priority (3GPP TS 38.413, 3GPP TS 36.423). Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..15 given in decimal.

cgrole:
Cell group role. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: mcg or scg, where mcg is only applicable to NR standalone.

chipset:
Chipset identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<vendor>.<variant>.<version>" matched by regular expression "(1[0-6]|[0-9])\\.(6[0-4]|[1-5]?[0-9])\\.(12[0-8]|1[01][0-9]|[1-9]?[0-9])", or a string constant "ref".

Description: Chipset identifier composed of three distinct elements:
- vendor: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..16
- variant: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..64
- version: 1-3 digit decimal number in range 0..128

UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting are represented internally as 0.0.0.

Example values: 0.0.0, 1.1.1, 1.2.3, 16.10.100, 16.64.128, ref.

imeisv:
International Mobile Station Equipment Identity Software Version. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<TAC><SNR><SVN>" matched by regular expression "[0-9]{10}[0-9fF]{4}[0-9]{2}", or string constant "ref".

Description: IMEISV composed of three distinct elements:
- TAC (Type Allocation Code): 8 digit decimal number
- SNR (or SN, Serial Number): 2 digit decimal number + 4 digit hexa-decimal number, last four digits are automatically masked with 0xFFFF to match with masked IMEISV
- SVN (Software Version Number): 2 digit decimal number

Example values: 1234567890123456, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890ffff12, ref.

imeitac:
Type Allocation Code (TAC) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 8 digit decimal number.

imeisvn:
Software Version Number (SVN) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 2 digit decimal number.

plmn:
Public Land and Mobile Network identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: A string matched by regular expression "[02-79][0-9][0-9]-[0-9][0-9][0-9]?".

Example values: 070-007, 070-07, 234-56.

qci:
QoSClass Identifier (3GPP TS 23.401). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

redcapue:
Reduced Capabilities UE indicator. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: Boolean
Description: RedCap UE identification received via LCID in MSG3 (see 3GPP TS 38.331).

rfsp:
Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

rrcEstResCause:
RRC establishment cause or RRC resume cause. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: One of emergency, highPriorityAccess, mt-Access, mo-Signaling, mo-Data, mo-VoiceCall, mo-VideoCall, mo-SMS, mps-PriorityAccess, or mcs-PriorityAccess.
Description: Establishment cause value received in RRC Setup Request message or resume cause received
in RRC Resume Request message (see 3GPP TS 38.331).
The received establishment cause or resume cause is valid in UE grouping framework when performing UE group evaluation during time specified by corresponding validity time attribute value in MO class UeGroupSelection.

snssai:
Single Network Slice Selection Assistance Information (3GPP TS 23.003). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: input option 1: String in format "<SST><SD>" matched by regular expression [0][x][0-9a-fA-F]{8} (8 digit hexa-decimal number).
Value: input option 2: Integer in range 0x0..0xffffffff given in hexadecimal.
Description: S-NSSAI is composed of two distinct elements:
- SST (Slice/Service Type): 2 digit hexa-decimal number
- SD (Slice Differentiator): 6 digit hexa-decimal number
The SD field has a reserved value "no SD value associated with the SST" defined as hexadecimal FFFFFF/ffffff.

Example values, input option 1:
- 0x050000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x2effffff (SST=0x2e,SD=0xffffff // no SD associated with the SST)

Example values, input option 2:
- 0x1 (SST=0x00,SD=0x000001)
- 0x50000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x150000EE (SST=0x15,SD=0x0000EE)

spid:
Subscriber Profile ID for RAT/Frequency Priority (3GPP TS 36.300). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

Operator Precedence Order:
=======================
The logical and relation operators are evaluated according to the precedence order listed below.

---------------------------------------------
1 (highest precedence)
< Less than
<= Less than or equal
> Greater than
>= Greater than or equal
== Equal
!= Not equal
-------------------------------------------
2 ! (Not)
---------------------------------------------
3 && (And)
---------------------------------------------
4 (lowest precedence)
|| (Or)
---------------------------------------------

The NOT operator "!" negates the following <ParentExpressionList>, <VariableExpression>, <FlowExpression> or an <ExpressionList> encapsulated in parenthesis.
Therefore, expression !a==b && c==d is equivalent to ((!(a==b)) && (c==d)) and different from !(a==b && c==d).
Expression !a==b and !(a==b) are equivalent.

Since AND operator "&&" has higher precedence than OR operator "||", a<b || a<c && c<d is equivalent to (a<b || (a<c && c<d)). Surround expression list including OR operator with parenthesis to force OR operator to be evaluated before AND operators outside of the expression list, for example (a<b || a<c) && c<d.

Examples:
=========

Simple one valued expressions:
plmn == 234-56
spid == 1
cgrole == mcg
arp > 3
snssai == 0xfedcba98
rrcEstResCause == mo-VoiceCall
imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12

imeisv == ref //Special <value> ref represents <ValueList> defined via imeiSvRef.
chipset == ref
chipset == 1.1.1 //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1.
chipset == 0.0.0 //Matches all UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting.

Value list expressions:
spid == {8,9,10,1,155}
!plmn == {234-56, 434-567}
chipset == {1.1.1, 1.1.2, 1.1.3, ref} //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1, 2 or 3, or the corresponding vendor, variant and version defined via chipsetRef.
imeisv == {1234567890FFFF12, ref, 1234567890FFFF13} //Matches all UEs with imeisv: TAC = 12345678, SNR = 90FFFF and SVN = 12 or 13, or the corresponding TAC, SN and SVN defined via imeiSvRef.

Equivalent expressions using ||:
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) //Equals to spid == {8, 9, 10, 1, 155}.
!(plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567) //Equals to !plmn == {234-56, 434-567}.

imeisv == ref || imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12|| imeisv == 1234567890FFFF13 //Equals to imeisv == {ref, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890FFFF13}.
chipset == 1.1.1 || chipset == ref || chipset == 1.1.2 // Equals to chipset == {1.1.1, ref, 1.1.2}.

Negative expressions:
!5qi==1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
5qi!=1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

Negative <FlowExpressions> that produce same result:
[!5qi==1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
[5qi!=1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

<FlowExpressionList> negative expressions:
!([5qi==1]) //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.
![5qi==1] //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.

Mixed examples:
spid == 1 && cgrole == mcg
!(spid != 1 || cgrole != mcg)
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) && (plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567)

Precedence given by "()" and sequence alter the evaluation order and result:
[5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5] //Equals to ([5qi==1] && chipset==ref) || (imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
([5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
chipset==ref || [5qi==1] && [5qi==5] && imeisv==ref

Examples of selection criteria that shall be avoided since they will always be evaluated to False. <FlowExpression> can be used in these cases.
5qi==5 && 5qi==9
snssai==0x15000000 && snssai==0x17000000
arp==5 && arp==10
qci==5 && qci==9

Example of selection criteria for UE variable snssai:
snssai>=15000000 && snssai<=15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 regardless of value of S-NSSAI SD part.
snssai==15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 and S-NSSAI SD part value equal to FFFFFF, meaning no SD value associated with the SST.

Flow expressions combined with UE variables:
plmn == 234-56 && [5qi==1] && [5qi==9] //Matches UE which has plmn equal to 234-56, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1, and any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9.
chipset==1.5.32 && [5qi==9] && ![5qi==1] //Matches UE which has chipset identifier equal to 1.5.32, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9, and no QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1.
[5qi==1 && snssai == 0xfedcba98] || ([5qi==2] && [snssai == 0xfedcba77]) //Matches UE which has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba98, or has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 2 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba77.

<AndOr> ::= "&&" | "||"
<Not> ::= "!"

<RelationalOperator> ::= "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">=" | ">"

A list of possible values can be specified in the form <Variable> == {<value1>, <value2>, ... , <valueN>}. This statement is equivalent to writing (<Variable> == <value1> || <Variable> == <value2> || ... || <Variable> == <valueN>).

Up to 4 <FlowExpression> can be defined in <SelectionCriteria>.

Whitespaces are allowed in the string for improved readability and are removed prior to evaluation.

Question mark (?) means zero or one occurrence. For example, <Not>? makes <Not> optional.

Syntax is case sensitive.

Semantic:
========
Selection criteria evaluation is defined by the following semantic rules.

If empty or set to empty string "", selection criteria always evaluates to True.

Selection criteria evaluation is done per UE with the current applicable UE <Variable> values as input. List of UE <Variable> values that are applicable to NR standalone and EN-DC, respectively, is defined in Variable Definitions section below.

Selection criteria for a UE is evaluated separately for each flow using applicable flow-dependent <Variable> together with rest of applicable UE <Variable>. For UE in NR standalone flow-dependent <Variable> 5qi, arp, and snssai are applicable. For UE in EN-DC flow-dependent <Variable> qci, and arp are applicable.

Selection criteria evaluates to True if any of the flows evaluates to True. If UE does not have a flow, flow-dependent <Variable> values are evaluated as unknown variable values. If selection criteria shall match combination of flow-dependent <Variable>, then <FlowExpression> and <FlowExpressionList> must be used.
Note: An <ExpressionList> defined as <VariableExpression> && <VariableExpression>, for which both <VariableExpression> relate to flow-dependent <Variable>, needs special attention.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi==5 && 5qi==9" always evaluate to False for UE in NR standalone even if UE has one flow with 5qi=5 and one flow with 5qi=9.

Example: <ExpressionList> = "5qi>=7 && 5qi<=11" will evaluate to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi between 7 and 11.

<FlowExpression> is defined as "["<ExpressionList>"]" and indicates that an <ExpressionList> is evaluated per QoS flow independent of other <ExpressionList>.

Example: <FlowExpressionList> = "[5qi==1] && [5qi==5]" evaluates to True for UE in NR standalone if UE has any flow with 5qi=1 and any flow with 5qi=5. In the example, [5qi==1] must match one flow, and [5qi==5] must match one flow.

<VariableExpression> evaluates to Unknown if <Variable> is not known or if the <Variable> value is not valid.
<VariableExpression> evaluates to True or False if <Variable> value is known and valid.

<Value> "ref" is a special <Value> of <Variable> representing <ValueList> defined via corresponding reference attribute. For <Variable> chipset, and imeisv, corresponding reference attribute is chipsetRef, and imeiSvRef respectively.

If reference attribute is empty, represented <ValueList> is empty.

The logical operators <AndOr> and <Not> apply three way logic as defined below:

F=False; T=True; U=Unknown
A=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>
B=Evaluation result of <ExpressionList> or <VariableExpression>

NOT operator:
A !A
-----------------
F T
U U
T F

AND operator:
A B A && B
-------------------
F F F
F T F
F U F
T F F
T T T
T U U
U F F
U T U
U U U

OR operator:
A B A || B
------------------
F F F
F T T
F U U
T F T
T T T
T U T
U F U
U T T
U U U

Variable Definitions:
=================

Allowed <Value> and <RelationalOperator> depend on <Variable> with limitations given below.

5qi:
5G QoS Identifier (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

arp:
Priority Level part of the Allocation and Retention Priority (3GPP TS 38.413, 3GPP TS 36.423). Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..15 given in decimal.

cgrole:
Cell group role. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: mcg or scg, where mcg is only applicable to NR standalone.

chipset:
Chipset identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<vendor>.<variant>.<version>" matched by regular expression "(1[0-6]|[0-9])\\.(6[0-4]|[1-5]?[0-9])\\.(12[0-8]|1[01][0-9]|[1-9]?[0-9])", or a string constant "ref".

Description: Chipset identifier composed of three distinct elements:
- vendor: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..16
- variant: 1-2 digit decimal number in range 0..64
- version: 1-3 digit decimal number in range 0..128

UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting are represented internally as 0.0.0.

Example values: 0.0.0, 1.1.1, 1.2.3, 16.10.100, 16.64.128, ref.

imeisv:
International Mobile Station Equipment Identity Software Version. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: String in format "<TAC><SNR><SVN>" matched by regular expression "[0-9]{10}[0-9fF]{4}[0-9]{2}", or string constant "ref".

Description: IMEISV composed of three distinct elements:
- TAC (Type Allocation Code): 8 digit decimal number
- SNR (or SN, Serial Number): 2 digit decimal number + 4 digit hexa-decimal number, last four digits are automatically masked with 0xFFFF to match with masked IMEISV
- SVN (Software Version Number): 2 digit decimal number

Example values: 1234567890123456, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890ffff12, ref.

imeitac:
Type Allocation Code (TAC) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 8 digit decimal number.

imeisvn:
Software Version Number (SVN) part of imeisv. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: 2 digit decimal number.

plmn:
Public Land and Mobile Network identifier. Applicable to both NR standalone and EN-DC.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: A string matched by regular expression "[02-79][0-9][0-9]-[0-9][0-9][0-9]?".

Example values: 070-007, 070-07, 234-56.

qci:
QoSClass Identifier (3GPP TS 23.401). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 0..255 given in decimal.

redcapue:
Reduced Capabilities UE indicator. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: Boolean
Description: RedCap UE identification received via LCID in MSG3 (see 3GPP TS 38.331).

rfsp:
Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority (3GPP TS 23.501). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

rrcEstResCause:
RRC establishment cause or RRC resume cause. Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, and !=.
Value: One of emergency, highPriorityAccess, mt-Access, mo-Signaling, mo-Data, mo-VoiceCall, mo-VideoCall, mo-SMS, mps-PriorityAccess, or mcs-PriorityAccess.
Description: Establishment cause value received in RRC Setup Request message or resume cause received
in RRC Resume Request message (see 3GPP TS 38.331).
The received establishment cause or resume cause is valid in UE grouping framework when performing UE group evaluation during time specified by corresponding validity time attribute value in MO class UeGroupSelection.

snssai:
Single Network Slice Selection Assistance Information (3GPP TS 23.003). Applicable to NR standalone.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: input option 1: String in format "<SST><SD>" matched by regular expression [0][x][0-9a-fA-F]{8} (8 digit hexa-decimal number).
Value: input option 2: Integer in range 0x0..0xffffffff given in hexadecimal.
Description: S-NSSAI is composed of two distinct elements:
- SST (Slice/Service Type): 2 digit hexa-decimal number
- SD (Slice Differentiator): 6 digit hexa-decimal number
The SD field has a reserved value "no SD value associated with the SST" defined as hexadecimal FFFFFF/ffffff.

Example values, input option 1:
- 0x050000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x2effffff (SST=0x2e,SD=0xffffff // no SD associated with the SST)

Example values, input option 2:
- 0x1 (SST=0x00,SD=0x000001)
- 0x50000EE (SST=0x05,SD=0x0000EE)
- 0x150000EE (SST=0x15,SD=0x0000EE)

spid:
Subscriber Profile ID for RAT/Frequency Priority (3GPP TS 36.300). Applicable to EN-DC.
Operator: ==, !=, <=, >=, <, and >.
Value: Integer in range 1..256 given in decimal.

Operator Precedence Order:
=======================
The logical and relation operators are evaluated according to the precedence order listed below.

---------------------------------------------
1 (highest precedence)
< Less than
<= Less than or equal
> Greater than
>= Greater than or equal
== Equal
!= Not equal
-------------------------------------------
2 ! (Not)
---------------------------------------------
3 && (And)
---------------------------------------------
4 (lowest precedence)
|| (Or)
---------------------------------------------

The NOT operator "!" negates the following <ParentExpressionList>, <VariableExpression>, <FlowExpression> or an <ExpressionList> encapsulated in parenthesis.
Therefore, expression !a==b && c==d is equivalent to ((!(a==b)) && (c==d)) and different from !(a==b && c==d).
Expression !a==b and !(a==b) are equivalent.

Since AND operator "&&" has higher precedence than OR operator "||", a<b || a<c && c<d is equivalent to (a<b || (a<c && c<d)). Surround expression list including OR operator with parenthesis to force OR operator to be evaluated before AND operators outside of the expression list, for example (a<b || a<c) && c<d.

Examples:
=========

Simple one valued expressions:
plmn == 234-56
spid == 1
cgrole == mcg
arp > 3
snssai == 0xfedcba98
rrcEstResCause == mo-VoiceCall
imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12

imeisv == ref //Special <value> ref represents <ValueList> defined via imeiSvRef.
chipset == ref
chipset == 1.1.1 //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1.
chipset == 0.0.0 //Matches all UEs that do not support chipset identifier reporting.

Value list expressions:
spid == {8,9,10,1,155}
!plmn == {234-56, 434-567}
chipset == {1.1.1, 1.1.2, 1.1.3, ref} //Matches all UEs with chipset identifier: vendor = 1, variant = 1 and version = 1, 2 or 3, or the corresponding vendor, variant and version defined via chipsetRef.
imeisv == {1234567890FFFF12, ref, 1234567890FFFF13} //Matches all UEs with imeisv: TAC = 12345678, SNR = 90FFFF and SVN = 12 or 13, or the corresponding TAC, SN and SVN defined via imeiSvRef.

Equivalent expressions using ||:
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) //Equals to spid == {8, 9, 10, 1, 155}.
!(plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567) //Equals to !plmn == {234-56, 434-567}.

imeisv == ref || imeisv == 1234567890FFFF12|| imeisv == 1234567890FFFF13 //Equals to imeisv == {ref, 1234567890FFFF12, 1234567890FFFF13}.
chipset == 1.1.1 || chipset == ref || chipset == 1.1.2 // Equals to chipset == {1.1.1, ref, 1.1.2}.

Negative expressions:
!5qi==1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
5qi!=1 //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

Negative <FlowExpressions> that produce same result:
[!5qi==1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.
[5qi!=1] //Matches flows with 5qi not equal to 1.

<FlowExpressionList> negative expressions:
!([5qi==1]) //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.
![5qi==1] //Matches UEs that do not have flows with 5qi 1.

Mixed examples:
spid == 1 && cgrole == mcg
!(spid != 1 || cgrole != mcg)
(spid == 8 || spid == 9 || spid == 10 || spid == 1 || spid == 155) && (plmn == 234-56 || plmn == 434-567)

Precedence given by "()" and sequence alter the evaluation order and result:
[5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5] //Equals to ([5qi==1] && chipset==ref) || (imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
([5qi==1] && chipset==ref || imeisv==ref) && [5qi==5]
[5qi==1] && (chipset==ref || imeisv==ref && [5qi==5])
chipset==ref || [5qi==1] && [5qi==5] && imeisv==ref

Examples of selection criteria that shall be avoided since they will always be evaluated to False. <FlowExpression> can be used in these cases.
5qi==5 && 5qi==9
snssai==0x15000000 && snssai==0x17000000
arp==5 && arp==10
qci==5 && qci==9

Example of selection criteria for UE variable snssai:
snssai>=15000000 && snssai<=15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 regardless of value of S-NSSAI SD part.
snssai==15FFFFFF //Matches UE which has a flow with S-NSSAI SST part equal to 15 and S-NSSAI SD part value equal to FFFFFF, meaning no SD value associated with the SST.

Flow expressions combined with UE variables:
plmn == 234-56 && [5qi==1] && [5qi==9] //Matches UE which has plmn equal to 234-56, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1, and any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9.
chipset==1.5.32 && [5qi==9] && ![5qi==1] //Matches UE which has chipset identifier equal to 1.5.32, any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 9, and no QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1.
[5qi==1 && snssai == 0xfedcba98] || ([5qi==2] && [snssai == 0xfedcba77]) //Matches UE which has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 1 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba98, or has any QoS flow with 5qi equal to 2 and snssai equal to 0xfedcba77.
Disturbances: Changing this attribute can cause loss of traffic.
